## 3. Label Files (`.txt` inside `labels/`)

Each image has a corresponding `.txt` file with the same name, stored under `labels/train/` or `labels/val/`. Each line in the file represents one annotated object.

**Format per line:**
```
<class_id> <x_center> <y_center> <width> <height>
```

All coordinates are **normalised** (0.0 to 1.0) relative to image dimensions.

```
# frame_0001.txt (example тАФ two objects annotated)
0 0.512 0.334 0.148 0.092
1 0.278 0.671 0.203 0.175
```

**Interpretation:**
- Line 1: Class `0` (helix), centered at (51.2%, 33.4%) of image, 14.8% wide, 9.2% tall
- Line 2: Class `1` (cluster), centered at (27.8%, 67.1%), 20.3% wide, 17.5% tall

**Why normalised coordinates?**  
Normalisation ensures label files remain valid when images are resized (preserving aspect ratio), eliminating the need to re-annotate after scaling.

---

## 4. What the Configuration Files Reveal

1. **Class taxonomy:** The YAML defines the problem space тАФ what the model will learn to recognise.
2. **Data splits:** Separate train/val paths enforce rigorous evaluation on unseen data.
3. **Annotation quality:** Poorly placed bounding boxes in `.txt` files directly degrade model accuracy.
4. **Scalability:** The flat text format is human-readable, version-controllable (Git), and tool-agnostic.

